Exploration of Prosper Loan Dataset¶

by Uzoamaka Umewuzie¶

Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset from loans as gathered by Prosper(the first peer-to-peer lending marketplace in the United States) containing 113,937 listing keys with 81 variables on each key, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, IsBorrowerHomeowner(whether or not the borrower owns a home), and many others.

The purpose of this analysis is to determine what factors influence the interest rate of borrowers' loan.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 113,937 loan records with 81 variables (including LoanOriginalAmount, BorrowerAPR, StatedMonthlyIncome, Term, ProsperRating (Alpha), IsBorrowerHomeowner, EmploymentStatus and many others). It also contains unique identifiers/primary keys which are found under the ListingKey and ListingNumber variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

When it comes to loans, while borrowers are more interested in obtaining loans at reasonable interest rates, lenders are more interested in recovering their money. Also, from the information above about the dataset, the BorrowerAPR column have 25 null values. Unlike interest rate(BorrowerRate), APR usually include charges or fees such as mortgage insurance, discount points, loan origination fee. It is therefore generally expected that the higher the interest rate, the higher the APR. On this note, my main feature of interest will be the BorrowerRate since BorrowerAPR has few null values. With this in mind, I am most interested in:

  1. Finding out what features are best for predicting the borrower's Interest Rate(BorrowerRate) for the loan.
  2. Borrowers' behaviour across months of the year.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Loan amount, stated monthly income of borrowers, employment status and whether or not they are homeowners will have an effect on the interest rate of loans. I expect that since homes/buildings are substantial collaterals, homeowners will have access to bigger loans at lesser interest rates, since loans with collaterals are referred to as secured loans.

Questions:¶

  1. How does StatedMonthlyIncome, Prosper Rating, Employment Status, Income Range affect the interest rates of borrowers' loan?
  2. Does whether or not a borrower own a home influence their interest rates and ability to obtain higher loan amounts?
  3. What is the borrowing pattern of borrowers across months of the year.

Before a loan is issued out by a loan bank, there must be a level of assurance pf the ability of the borrower to pay back the loan. StatedMonthlyIncome, Employment Status and Income Range are variables contained in the dataset which tells of the financial capacity of the borrower. For this reason, they will be used in determining effects on interest rates.

Collaterals are also important factors to consider in loan listings. Being a homeowner could most likely increase a borrower's chance of getting higher loan amounts since loan banks categorize loans with collaterals as secured. The variable, IsBorrowerHomeowner would be used to investigate effects on Interest rates and loan amounts.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of interest rate(BorrowerRate) looks multimodal. Most of the values are at the range of 0.05 and 0.4. More borrowers seem to request for loan amounts in multples of 1000, and Debt Consolidation was the highest reason borrowers listed as the purpose of the loan.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The distributions of stated monthly income is highly skewed to the right. Most stated monthly incomes are less than $40k, but some of them are incredibly high, like greater than 100k. Surprisingly, most of borrowers with greater than 100k monthly income only loan less than 5k dollars. So, the very large stated monthly income may be made up. Overall, Less than 0.3 percent borrowers have stated monthly income greater than 30k, these can be seemed as outlier for the following analysis, so it is better to remove borrower records with income greater than 30k.

To tidy the data in order to enable addition of relevant features like ListingCreation_month, I changed the datatype for ListingCreationDate from object to datetime. This is to help me figure out the loan application pattern/trend of borrowers across the year.

For ListingCategory variable, column name and datatype was changed, and values had to be replaced from numerical listings to categorical listings as indicated on the data dictionary . This is because, since listings number from 1-20, creating a legend for the purpose of visualization would be cumbersome or distracting to the audience.

The correlation coefficient did improve as a result of the removal of less occuring monthly income. Correlation between StatedMonthlyIncome and Loan Amount became more positive with a coefficient of 0.4, showing that borrowers with higher monthly income would have access to more loan amount. The correlation coefficient of Interest rate and loan original amount is -0.33. This shows that these two variables are negatively correlated, which agrees with our hypothesis, that is the more the loan amount, the lower the interest rate.

There is a strong positive correlation between APR nd Interest Rate, with a correlation coefficient of 0.99. the higher the interest rate, the higher the APR. Prediction for null APR values in the dataset can be done using the Interest Rates of the loan amount. This confirms the expectation that with the inclusion of charges or fees such as mortgage insurance, discount points, loan origination fee, APRs are proportional to Interest Rates. This also explains why the relationship between APR and interest rate versus loan amount look very similar.

Borrowers who enjoy lower interest rates give better ratings.

The loan original amount is positively correlated with the stated monthly income, it makes sense since borrowers with more monthly income could loan more money.

Next, I'll investigate if being a homeowner influences the relationship between loan amount and interest rate.

Out[36]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x18e2e0c56a0>

The non-positional encoding of IsBorrowerHomeowner as a third variable using color, it is seen that most borrowers who took loans higher than 25,000 enjoyed interest rates of less than 0.2. Interest rates greater than 0.4 were found to be paid only by borrowers who aren't home owners even though their loan amounts were less than

Homeowners are probably able to access more loan amounts with respect to the current value of the home. This is because the loaners need assurance that they will be able to get back all their money if the borrower isn't able to keep up with payment. Also, for borrowers(non-homeowners)who get high interest rate even at low loan amounts, this could be because these loans are not secured as they do not involve collateral. Secured loans usually have lower interest rates than unsecured loans because the bank has a way to recoup its money if you do not pay.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

In the multivariate exploration of data, I observed the relationship between Interest rate(BorrowerRate) and loan amount by looking at the impact of the Prosper rating. The multivariate exploration showed that the relationship between borrower APR and loan amount turns from negative to slightly positive when the Prosper ratings increased from HR to AA. It was observed that borrowing pattern of both homeowners and non-homeowners are similar across the months of the year. But, compared to non-homeowners, homeowners borrowed more money.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Ratings doesn't have any effect on the relationship between Loan Term and Interest Rate. Irrespective of the borrowers rating, interest rate will increase with longer loan term. Ratings only get better with decrease in interest rate. Another interaction of interest is that the borrower APR and loan amount is negatively correlated when the Prosper ratings are from HR to B, but the correlation turns slightly positive when the ratings are A and AA.

Conclusions¶

In conclusion, increased income range amounts to increased loan amounts. Increased loan amounts amounts to lower interest rates. Lower interest rates amounts to better ratings. Homeowners, as a result of the availability of colaterals and its implication of a secured loan, have access to higher loan amounts at less interest rates.
